Write integration tests and create a README. This phase validates the entire app works end-to-end.

## 1. backend/tests/test_integration.py

Write a comprehensive end-to-end test that exercises the FULL user flow:

```python
async def test_full_date_flow(client, db_session):
    # 1. Register 6 users (3 male, 3 female) with .utoronto.ca emails
    # 2. Verify all emails
    # 3. Login all users, get tokens
    # 4. Create profiles for all (with photos, bio, interests, vibe answers)
    # 5. Create date requests: all want "bowling", group_size=6, same availability
    # 6. Run batch matching (via admin endpoint — register an admin user first)
    # 7. Verify: 1 group created with all 6 members
    # 8. Verify: group chat room created with 6 participants
    # 9. Get group detail as a member — verify public profiles, no private prefs
    # 10. Get icebreakers — verify 3 returned
    # 11. Get venue suggestions — verify bowling venues returned
    # 12. Submit feedback for all 6 members:
    #     - User M1 interested in F1 and F2
    #     - User F1 interested in M1
    #     - User F2 interested in M2
    #     - User M2 interested in F2
    #     - Others: not interested
    #     - User M3 blocks F3
    # 13. Verify: Match created for M1-F1 (mutual) and M2-F2 (mutual)
    # 14. Verify: No match for M1-F2 (one-sided)
    # 15. Verify: BlockedPair created for M3-F3
    # 16. Verify: 1-on-1 chat rooms created for both matches
    # 17. Get matches as M1 — verify F1 is the partner with chat_room_id
    # 18. List chat rooms as M1 — verify both group chat and direct chat appear
```

